and effectiveness of their democratic institutions. Imperfect Democracies brings together Canadian and American scholars to compare and contrast the democratic deficit in the two nations. Blending normative theory and empirical analysis, they focus on three key questions: Why talk about a democratic deficit? In what ways are Canadian and American democracies falling short? What can be done to remedy the deficit? An important contribution to the field of democratic theory and the study of democratic institutions, this timely book will spark debate on both sides of the border.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracy -- Canada. 0aDemocracy -- United States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBeetham, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoatright, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourtney, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDocherty, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLei, Ethan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenard, Patti Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenard, Patti Tamara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcDonald, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunro, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevitte, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorris, Pippa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPonet, David L., econ